                ul.navbar-nav.text-right
                    include ./partials/welcome_new

        // Masthead
        header#top.masthead.text-center.text-black
            .overlay
            .container
                row
                    .col-xl-9.mx-auto
                        h1.mb(style={color:'#495057'}) What does it all mean?
                        include ./partials/messages
        // Icons Grid
        section.features-icons.bg-light
            .container
                h3.text-center(style={color:'#495057'}) Air quality categories and general health advice
                p.lead.text-center(style='font-size:110%;')
                    | All information is provided by EPA Victoria. For more information visit their
                    a.d-inline(href='https://www.epa.vic.gov.au')  website
                    | .
                br
                h3(style={color:"#64a13c"}) Good
                p It's a good day to be outside.
                h3(style={color:"#eac51c"}) Moderate
                p The air quality is okay, but it could change soon.
                p It’s okay to be outside but watch for changes in air quality around you.
                h3(style={color:"#d67900"}) Poor
                p The air is probably dusty or smoky.
                    a(href='https://www.epa.vic.gov.au/for-community/monitoring-your-environment/about-epa-airwatch/air-pollution-sensitivity')  Sensitive groups
                    |  may experience symptoms like coughing or shortness of breath.
                ul
                    li If you are sensitive to air pollution, spend less time outside in the smoke or dust and follow your treatment plan. Reduce prolonged or heavy physical activity.
                    li If you are coughing or short of breath, avoid being outside in the smoke or dust.
                    li Close your windows and doors to keep smoke and dust out of your home.
                    li If you are worried about your symptoms, see your doctor or call
                        a(href='https://www2.health.vic.gov.au/primary-and-community-health/primary-care/nurse-on-call')  Nurse On Call
                        |  on 1300 606 024.
                    li Seek urgent medical help if anyone has trouble breathing or tightness in the chest. Call 000 for an ambulance.
                h3(style={color:"#a90737"}) Very poor
                p The air is probably very dusty or smoky. Everyone could be experiencing symptoms like coughing or shortness of breath.
                ul
                    li Listen to your
                        a(href='https://www.abc.net.au/local/')  local emergency radio station
                        |  or visit
                        a(href='http://www.emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/')  Emergency Vic
                        |  for advice.
                    li Avoid being outside in the smoke or dust. Reduce prolonged or heavy physical activity.
                    li If you are sensitive to air pollution, follow your treatment plan. Avoid physical activity outdoors.
                    li Close your windows and doors to keep smoke and dust out of your home.
                    li If you think the air in your home is uncomfortable, consider going to an air-conditioned building like a library or shopping centre for a break if it’s safe to do so.
                    li If you are worried about your symptoms, see your doctor or call
                        a(href='https://www2.health.vic.gov.au/primary-and-community-health/primary-care/nurse-on-call')  Nurse On Call
                        |  on 1300 606 024.
                    li Seek urgent medical help if anyone has trouble breathing or tightness in the chest. Call 000 for an ambulance.
                h3(style={color:"#50051e"}) Hazardous
                p The air is probably extremely dusty or smoky. Everyone could be experiencing symptoms like coughing or shortness of breath.
                ul
                    li Listen to your
                        a(href='https://www.abc.net.au/local/')  local emergency radio station
                        |  or visit
                        a(href='http://www.emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/')  Emergency Vic
                        |  for advice.
                    li Stay indoors away from smoke and dust.
                    li If you are sensitive to air pollution, follow your treatment plan. If you can, remain indoors and keep physical activity levels as low as possible.
                    li Close your windows and doors to keep smoke and dust out of your home.
                    li If you think the air in your home is uncomfortable, consider going to an air-conditioned building like a library or shopping centre for a break if it’s safe to do so.
                    li If you are worried about your symptoms, see your doctor or call
                        a(href='https://www2.health.vic.gov.au/primary-and-community-health/primary-care/nurse-on-call')  Nurse On Call
                        |  on 1300 606 024.
                    li Seek urgent medical help if anyone has trouble breathing or tightness in the chest. Call 000 for an ambulance.
                h3(style={color:'#495057'}) More Information
                ul
                    li Information about how EPA air quality categories are calculated is available
                        a(href='https://www.epa.vic.gov.au/for-community/monitoring-your-environment/about-epa-airwatch/calculate-air-quality-categories')  here.
                    li Information about EPA's accreditation is available
                        a(href='https://www.epa.vic.gov.au/for-community/monitoring-your-environment/about-epa-airwatch/accreditation-of-epa-air-quality-monitoring')  here.
